50|$|<b>In</b> 1937, <b>the</b> Nazis {{constructed}} <b>the</b> Buchenwald concentration <b>camp,</b> near Weimar, Germany. The motto Jedem das Seine {{was placed}} <b>in</b> <b>the</b> <b>camp's</b> main entrance gate. The gates {{were designed by}} Franz Ehrlich, {{a former student of}} the Bauhaus art school, who had been imprisoned <b>in</b> <b>the</b> <b>camp</b> because he was a communist.|$|R
25|$|<b>The</b> living {{conditions}} <b>in</b> <b>the</b> <b>camp</b> were extremely poor, it brought infection and illness and, consequently, plagues that killed {{a large number}} of <b>the</b> people <b>in</b> <b>the</b> <b>camp.</b> They were buried on a valley nearby that used to be a burial place of Jews hundreds of years ago.|$|R
